00:11:46,719 --> 00:11:49,482
There are certain genres that obviously cater very well to this.

204
00:11:49,762 --> 00:11:55,368
If we think of, as an example, which we're going to look at just now, if we look at simulators,

205
00:11:56,148 --> 00:12:01,733
particularly if we think about maybe a car engine simulator, you could tap into a community

206
00:12:01,874 --> 00:12:03,936
of enthusiasts about car engines.

207
00:12:04,196 --> 00:12:08,580
These are not people who generally play many video games, for example, so you're not competing

208
00:12:08,660 --> 00:12:09,981
in the space of video games.

209
00:12:10,442 --> 00:12:14,443
you're actually bringing something new to an established community

210
00:12:14,803 --> 00:12:19,745
that has a very specific hobby and is generally quite hungry for quality content.

211
00:12:20,265 --> 00:12:23,907
And so if you come along and you give them a video game of this topic,

212
00:12:24,387 --> 00:12:28,548
chances are that they'll be very enthusiastic about it and kind of back you right from the start

213
00:12:28,949 --> 00:12:33,050
and also help you shape the game design and game mechanics in a way that is meaningful

214
00:12:33,590 --> 00:12:34,691
to this kind of community.

215
00:12:35,931 --> 00:12:40,214
The other big thing I feel about working with the niche titles is kind of,

216
00:12:41,374 --> 00:12:45,577
I guess if you've been doing game design for a while, you might be familiar with the fact that

217
00:12:46,117 --> 00:12:52,221
when you're doing games, you try and give players a relatively constrained set of rules to work within.

218
00:12:52,761 --> 00:12:56,703
If a player has too much freedom, they often find themselves confused,

