00:12:56,783 --> 00:13:01,486
which leads to frustration, which leads to anger, which leads to one star in the refund, so to speak.

220
00:13:02,527 --> 00:13:05,670
This same concept applies extremely well to game development, of course.

221
00:13:05,930 --> 00:13:09,133
If as a game developer I'm just trying to do something entirely new,

222
00:13:09,153 --> 00:13:13,758
that doesn't have an established design language, doesn't have an established audience...

223
00:13:14,873 --> 00:13:18,215
The chances of, you know, obviously having a huge hit

224
00:13:18,655 --> 00:13:20,696
are tiny, although of course, there are people

225
00:13:20,756 --> 00:13:23,097
who work in that area and that's great for them,

226
00:13:23,157 --> 00:13:24,818
but for the rest of us mortals,

227
00:13:25,758 --> 00:13:27,439
helping, it's really helpful, I guess,

228
00:13:27,479 --> 00:13:30,340
to work within an established set of constraints

229
00:13:30,880 --> 00:13:32,801
and a language that's familiar to your players

230
00:13:32,961 --> 00:13:34,582
so that you can kind of tap into that.

231
00:13:35,302 --> 00:13:38,664
And it's more about, I guess, iteration and improving

232
00:13:38,744 --> 00:13:40,925
rather than trying to come up with something entirely new.

233
00:13:42,052 --> 00:13:46,775
And the third fairly obvious one is we're trying to avoid that market saturation as we were talking about before.

234
00:13:46,855 --> 00:13:48,476
We don't like market saturation.

235
00:13:48,676 --> 00:13:49,457
It's a real thing.

236
00:13:50,117 --> 00:13:59,423
